<HEADLINE>
<P>
VOTERS FACE 28 INITIATIVES IN NOVEMBER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gov. George Deukmejian is running around the state pitching his pet project of 
putting prison inmates to work in outside industry. He says it's a great way to 
make prisoners productive and also would help in their rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
Don't be fooled. 
</P>
<P>
What the Deukmejian proposal (Prop. 139) would really do is put felons in 
direct, unfair competition with the regular work force. Employers would be 
favorably disposed to hire them because of the tax incentives included in this 
measure, not to mention the advantages of having a cheap, submissive labor 
pool. 
</P>
<P>
There's no evidence that this program would save taxpayers a dime. In fact, 
administration and enforcement of the law could be very costly, because each of 
California's 58 counties would be free to devise its own set of rules for using 
and supervising inmate labor. Prisoners would be exploited and workers who 
haven't committed a crime would be severely penalized if this amendment were 
adopted. 
</P>
<P>
THOMAS J. VANDEVELD, President 
</P>
<P>
United Food &amp; Commercial Workers 
</P>
<P>
Union, Local 135, San Diego 
</P>
</TEXT>
