<HEADLINE>
<P>
HANDLING OF POSTER SITUATION WAS TRAGEDY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
We at The Works Gallery are appalled by the total lack of vision and courage 
shown by the Orange County Airport Arts Commission and the Airport 
Administration regarding the commissioned poster by artist Jim Morphesis 
("Airport Poster Plan Melts Away, but Not the Art Uproar," Sept. 2.) I am 
horrified by the lack of integrity exemplified by our civic "leaders" in the 
process of effectively censoring a truly beautiful work of art. 
</P>
<P>
Beyond the obvious stupidity displayed by the Airport administration in 
censoring a work of art no more "obscene" than any classical Greek or Roman 
work of art, the handling of this situation is a real tragedy. When one 
individual -- (airport commissioner) Robert Cashman -- has the power to 
override an entire committee which voted 9-0 to support the work of art and the 
selected poster, and to make all decisions pertaining to the art collection of 
the airport -- that is a tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
When a single Orange County resident can elect himself "tastemaker" for an 
entire community -- after he is quoted in the press as saying, "If they gave us 
Michelangelo's 'David' today, I'd put it in a warehouse . . ." -- that is a 
tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
It is one thing for a printer to pull his offer to print a poster he doesn't 
like; this is a free country. But when that printer also is an official on the 
committee deciding the poster's fate -- that is where it gets interesting. This 
conflict of interests is the direct result of poorly handled business planning, 
typical of the entire airport project. How Cashman could turn a unanimous vote 
in support of the poster on Wednesday into a vote of "Gee, I guess it's too 
late to print it now, that's just too bad" 72 hours later, is another example 
of back-room politics and nepotism. 
</P>
<P>
The Morphesis incident is just one more example of the growing atmosphere of 
bureaucratic restraint on the arts being manifested again and again by 
individuals who feel they are qualified to decide for the rest of us what is 
and what isn't good. I feel it is ironic that the image that Cashman found 
offensive was that of Icarus, a man who fancied himself a god and in the effort 
to emulate one caused his own demise. Maybe Robert Cashman has just flown too 
close to the sun. 
</P>
<P>
MARK MOORE 
</P>
<P>
Director, The Works Gallery 
</P>
<P>
Costa Mesa 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, "Winged Man" by Jim Morphesis. Poster art for new airport was canceled. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
