<HEADLINE>
<P>
ENTERTAINERS SWEETEN WALK IN GARDENS; 
</P>
<P>
MUSIC: ABOUT 15 GROUPS REPRESENTING DIFFERENT CULTURES WILL PERFORM IN DESCANSO 
GARDEN NOOKS FOR VISITORS WHO STROLL PAST TODAY AND SUNDAY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE WYMA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Strolling entertainers are nothing new, but it is the audience that will do the 
strolling at Descanso Gardens during the Los Angeles Festival's closing weekend 
today and Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
Performers will set up in nooks and crannies throughout the lush Los Angeles 
County park in La Canada Flintridge while the public circulates like diners 
sampling food from an exotic smorgasbord. 
</P>
<P>
"The sound will lead you through the gardens," said Patty Mannatt, special 
events coordinator for the county Department of Arboreta and Botanic Gardens. 
"Descanso Gardens has a lot of camellia trees that have grown into a camellia 
forest, and there are lots of little pockets that will hold 25 or 50 people who 
can stop and listen to a performer." 
</P>
<P>
Organizers opted for the unusual setup in part to give people a chance to see 
performers who have appeared at locations throughout the Los Angeles area. 
</P>
<P>
Among the groups scheduled: the Chinese Classical Music Ensemble; Garba-Ras, 
Indian folk dancers who invite audience participation; the Nigerian Talking 
Drum Ensemble; the World Kulintang Institute, performers of gong music of the 
Muslim Philippines; Bibak, 130 performers from the Philippines; Los Pregoneros 
del Puerto featuring harp virtuoso Jose Pepe Gutierrez and Hawaiian dancer 
Randy Chang. 
</P>
<P>
In all, about 15 groups are scheduled, including last minute additions like the 
traditional Bolivian music group, Miriam Mita and Ayllu Sankayo. 
</P>
<P>
Schedules of final times and locations of performances will be handed out at 
the park entrance. 
</P>
<P>
"There will always be something going on," said Peggy Riley, producer of the 
Descanso Gardens weekend. "It's very free-form. People can sit and listen, then 
move to a new place and hear something new." 
</P>
<P>
The park will open at 9 a.m.; entertainment begins at noon each day and ends at 
6 p.m., although Sunday's program is expected to run until dusk to mark the 
festival's closing. There are some benches, but most seating will be on the 
ground. 
</P>
<P>
Music is presented every Sunday during the summer on the main lawn, but this is 
the first time that artists will play at various spots. Simultaneous 
performances raise the prospect of cacophony, but organizers said they expect 
no problem. The park, a popular wedding site with a waterfall, is large enough 
and the vegetation thick enough to keep the music from clashing, they said. 
</P>
<P>
Traffic and parking are not expected to present problems, either. Mannatt said 
that an annual garden festival attracts about as many people as are expected 
this weekend and that "people get in and out just fine." 
</P>
<P>
Festival organizers hope to draw 4,000 people each day. Descanso Gardens holds 
2,000. 
</P>
<P>
"If everyone came at the same time, we'd be in trouble," said Mannatt, "but 
that's not going to happen. People will be coming and going all day." 
</P>
<P>
Both Mannatt and Gail Boatwright, head of the Descanso Gardens Guild, a 
nonprofit support group, said no community opposition has surfaced to the Los 
Angeles Festival weekend. The guild sponsors all public events at the gardens. 
</P>
<P>
"We approve of what they're doing and we're cooperating," Boatwright said, 
adding that she does not fear damage by crowds to the garden's plants and 
lawns. 
</P>
<P>
"That's quite a lot of people for the area, but we're hoping they'll be spread 
out throughout the day," she said. "There will be monitors to make sure that 
groups of people don't get too big." 
</P>
<P>
Ethnic food will be sold near the parking area and there are picnic tables 
nearby. Eating is permitted on the main lawn area but not in the rest of the 
park because it is a garden. Alcoholic beverages are prohibited. 
</P>
<P>
Admission is $3 admission for adults, $1.50 for senior citizens and students, 
and 75 cents for children 5 to 12. Children under 5 are free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, "The sound will lead you through" the Descanso Gardens today and Sunday. 
GEORGE ROSE / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
