<HEADLINE>
<P>
THRIFT'S CAMPAIGN TO RELY ON (FREE) FLIGHTS OF FANCY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES S. GRANELLI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
IRVINE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
American Savings Bank started its most ambitious sales campaign ever Friday by 
offering free and discounted flights on Continental Airlines to destinations in 
Europe, Asia, Mexico, Hawaii and 87 U.S. cities. 
</P>
<P>
In a bid to drum up more deposits and loans, the thrift will begin advertising 
the program Sunday with a TV ad showing a silhouetted couple "Dancing the 
Continental." 
</P>
<P>
Banks and thrifts have long enticed customers with giveaways -- usually 
toasters and other small appliances. American's offer of plane trips is an 
unusually extensive promotion. 
</P>
<P>
"This is the most aggressive campaign we've ever sponsored," American 
spokeswoman Casey MacKenzie said. 
</P>
<P>
The thrift, which has $16.5 billion in assets and earned $214.2 million last 
year, would not disclose how much the promotion is costing. 
</P>
<P>
Depositors who open certificates of deposit with $2,500, annuities, checking 
accounts and charge card accounts can get discounts on travel. A $20,000 
certificate of deposit earns a customer a free round-trip companion ticket to 
France, England, Japan, Hawaii or any of Continental's 87 U.S. destinations. 
</P>
<P>
An adjustable-rate mortgage for $50,000 or more brings two free round-trip 
tickets to anywhere Continental flies in Mexico, Hawaii or the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
AMERICAN SAVINGS BANK; FLYING; BANKS -- ORANGE COUNTY; BANKING INDUSTRY -- 
ORANGE COUNTY 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
