<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLAYWRIGHT REJECTS COUPLE'S BIGOTRY CHARGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICK VANDERKNYFF 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a phone interview Friday, playwright Christopher Durang rejected charges 
that his play "Sister Mary Ignatius Explains It All for You" constitutes 
"anti-religious bigotry," as has been charged by a Costa Mesa couple who are 
protesting a local production. 
</P>
<P>
"I disagree with calling the play bigoted, and I bristle at it," said Durang, 
who in writing the play drew from his own experiences as a student in Catholic 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
"What they're calling bigotry is really criticism," he said. "Does that mean 
that one can't criticize the church's stand on birth control?" 
</P>
<P>
"Sister Mary" was the subject of similar controversies in the early to 
mid-'80s. Durang said the uproar has died down in recent years but that he is 
not surprised it has resurfaced. 
</P>
<P>
"The Feeneys (the Costa Mesa couple) are certainly in their right to protest 
and to try to change laws. I just hope they don't succeed. It's not appropriate 
to limit free speech that way," Durang said. 
</P>
<P>
John and Ernie Feeney have complained to the Costa Mesa City Council that a 
Costa Mesa Civic Playhouse production of "Sister Mary" violates newly adopted 
restrictions against "religious or political activity" by artistic groups 
receiving municipal grants. The city has given the nonprofit Playhouse $20,000 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
But Durang said he does not quite believe claims that the fight is over public 
funding, and not over censorship. 
</P>
<P>
"At heart," he said, the Feeneys "want to stop my play being spoken, and that 
is being a censor." RICK VANDERKNYFF 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
SISTER MARY IGNATIUS EXPLAINS IT ALL FOR YOU (PLAY); COSTA MESA (CA) -- 
FINANCES; GRANTS; CENSORSHIP; ARTS -- FINANCES; COSTA MESA CIVIC PLAYHOUSE; 
DURANG, CHRISTOPHER 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091590-0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 276762 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 15, 1990, Saturday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<P>
MICHEL CAMILO 
</P>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 2; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
759 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIERY JAZZ PIANIST CAMILO TAKES NOTE OF HIS CRITICS; 
</P>
<P>
MUSIC: THE DOMINICAN SAYS HIS FAST-PACED STYLE ISN'T AN AFFECTATION. HE PLAYS 
THE COACH HOUSE ON SUNDAY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON HECKMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I guess you could call me a kind of hot-blooded person. I think quickly, I 
talk quickly, and when I play, I hear all these notes. It's not that I'm trying 
to show off, it's just the way I hear music." 
</P>
<P>
Michel Camilo, who plays Sunday night at the Coach House in San Juan 
Capistrano, is in fact one of the fieriest pianists to come down the jazz pike 
since Oscar Peterson. His work snaps, crackles and pops with explosive 
technical energy. 
</P>
<P>
"I know I'm sometimes accused of having too much technique," Camilo 
acknowledged. "But if everybody played alike, music would be boring. What makes 
this life interesting -- and jazz in particular -- is personality. And that's 
what I try to bring to my playing. 
</P>
<P>
"Look at the players I've been most influenced by, players like Phineas 
Newborn, Oscar Peterson, Bud Powell and Bill Evans. They all play a lot of 
notes too. But they also have their own kind of minimalism, and so do I, I 
hope." 
</P>
<P>
A good part of the Dominican Republic native's technical expertise traces to 
extensive classical training. A youthful prodigy in a family that already had 
two generations of composers and performers, he began writing his first 
compositions at age 5 and was playing major recitals before he was a teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
"I guess," he said with a laugh, "that I'd rather not throw away all those 
painful years of practice and learning to play the instrument properly." 
</P>
<P>
Still, Camilo seems to have made an effort to counteract some of the criticism 
with his new Columbia/Epic album, "On The Other Hand." 
</P>
<P>
"I chose (that title) for a reason," he said. "It's like I'm saying, 'Sure, I 
can play fast, but, on the other hand. . . .' I see it as a kind of subtle way 
of letting people know that there are different aspects to my playing. 
</P>
<P>
"They think of me as a fiery player, but the album shows that I can write for 
horns, that I love ensemble work, and that I sometimes love to play tender 
music. It's like I'm flipping over the coin to show the other possibilities." 
</P>
<P>
Camilo, bassist Michael Bowie and drummer Cliff Almond will demonstrate some of 
those other possibilities at the Coach House with numbers from the new album as 
well as selections from his first two chart-topping releases, "Why Not" (the 
title song won a Grammy in 1983 for Manhattan Transfer) and "On Fire." 
</P>
<P>
Many of the pieces reflect a blending of his Caribbean heritage with his 
experiences living in New York City for more than a decade. Curiously, however, 
when Camilo arrived in the city, there were few Caribbean traces in his 
playing; he was a hard bop player, pure and simple. 
</P>
<P>
"That's what I used to play in the Dominican Republic," he recalled. "I know 
that sounds strange, but when you live on an island, you tend to look outside 
for influences. And all the records I listened to were hard bop. 
</P>
<P>
"Then, when I came to New York, there were so many different clubs, with so 
many musicians who came here to measure themselves. . . . If you're going to 
survive, you have to start thinking about what you can do that will be 
different, that will help you stand out from the crowd." 
</P>
<P>
Camilo's solution was to dip into his own background. "I said to myself, 'Wait 
a minute, I'm not just a hard bop player. I've got all these influences, all 
this other life experience, that I can use in my music.' And that's how I began 
to write music that had a little Caribbean flavor." 
</P>
<P>
He further developed his music by applying a few methods from his classical 
training. "Classical pianists really know how to milk a melody, and I use that 
approach. I try to find a shape for a song or a solo, something that makes it 
more than a stream of notes and phrases -- something with a beginning, a middle 
and an ending. And that's another place where the facility I have on the 
instrument has helped me. 
</P>
<P>
"But the bottom line for me is this: Does it move you or doesn't it move you? 
Is it touching something inside or isn't it? It's not how many notes you play, 
it's whether you're saying something or not. Whether you're painting the right 
picture. 
</P>
<P>
"Music is a language, the language of the soul. Especially jazz music. It's so 
here, now, right at this very moment. And that's what I've always loved about 
jazz. That's why I play it -- the challenge and the excitement and the 
spontaneity of instant composition. It's living music, on the edge. That's the 
risk of it. And I love living risky." 
</P>
<P>
 Michel Camilo and Ric Flauding play Sunday at 8 p.m. at the Coach House, 33157 
Camino Capistrano, San Juan Capistrano. Tickets: $15. Information: (714) 
496-8930. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Michel Camilo's bottom line is: "Does it move you? Is it touching. . . 
.?" 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
