<HEADLINE>
<P>
NUTS AND BOLTS; 
</P>
<P>
FORMICA NOT JUST FOR THE KRAMDENS ANYMORE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK MOTT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Formica, traditionally, has had about the same effect on Americans as jail. 
We'll concede that it's probably necessary in the public sector, but we 
wouldn't want it anywhere near our house. 
</P>
<P>
When it first appeared in the 1950s, Formica was the interior lineman of 
building materials: functional, durable and nobody's idea of subtle beauty, 
able to withstand heroic amounts of grime and still come clean. It was the 
roadside diner's shield against the world, covering countertops from coast to 
coast with low-maintenance -- but nonetheless ghastly -- colors, reeking of 
fried onions and Pine-Sol. 
</P>
<P>
In the home, however, Formica was strictly for the Kramdens. It was the table 
top of choice for people with children who threw food. You could hose it down, 
but you didn't want to put the Waterford on it. 
</P>
<P>
Today, however, you can use that veteran laminate material in your kitchen and 
bathroom without risking turning them into a knockoff of every beanery in the 
world named EAT. Formica has gone uptown. 
</P>
<P>
Don't worry; it's still Formica. It's still resistant to most of the slings and 
arrows of outrageous fortune, like strained beets and certain low-impact 
kitchen explosions. But instead of looking like the centerpiece of a cartoon 
nightmare, with swirls here and whirls there, all on a background of thundering 
yellow, today's Formica can be had in such incarnations as Nile Dorian Marble, 
Bronze Lacque Metallique and Vicuna Milano Stripe. 
</P>
<P>
"The patterns and the colors have been so expanded that now you have a rainbow 
of things to work with," said Mary Knott, a residential space planner and owner 
of Mary Fisher Designs in San Marino. 
</P>
<P>
Knott, who will speak about the uses of Formica at the Orange County Interior 
Design and Home Decorating Show at the Orange County Fairgrounds on Sept. 22 
and 23, said the popularity of the original Formica was diluted not only by the 
limited designs available at the time, but by cheap imitations. 
</P>
<P>
"The patterns they came out with at the time, like the boomerang pattern, for 
instance, were very Art Deco, with blues and pinks and yellows, and the 
appliances then followed suit in that color range," Knott said. "They were 
quite limited and they didn't have the subtle color changes they do now. And, 
as with many other things, mass merchandisers get knockoffs that are made from 
cheap materials and use them in a way that those materials were never meant to 
be used." 
</P>
<P>
What can you use Formica for now? Just about anything except a floor covering, 
Knott said. 
</P>
<P>
"So many people think of laminate materials strictly as countertops," she said. 
"But one of the best surfaces to use it on is cabinetry. That and wall 
surfacing is where I think you're going to see more and more builders and 
contractors using it." 
</P>
<P>
Unlike the plain vanilla days, this doesn't mean simply slapping a sheet of 
Formica on a surface, said Knott. The Formica Corp. has come up with a laminate 
material they call Colorcore that is "solid color all the way through. You can 
literally layer these materials and make all kinds of incredible designs. The 
only limitations are your imagination and your pocketbook." 
</P>
<P>
The traditional Formica laminate -- which is still available -- is bonded to a 
dark-colored backing that is revealed when the material is cut at, say, the 
edge of a counter. Colorcore is the same thickness, but the backing is 
eliminated. The color is solid throughout. 
</P>
<P>
"You can bevel it, you can round it off, you can do any kind of edge treatment 
you want," Knott said. "You can take layers of it and make striping and banding 
and wild stuff like pin stripes and make very creative looks." 
</P>
<P>
How creative? Any shape you can cut is fair game. Knott said she had heard of 
one application on a wall that involved layering the laminate and cutting one 
layer to resemble ripped construction paper. 
</P>
<P>
Also, she said, it's possible to pile on multiple layers and then cut geometric 
designs through the layers with a router, allowing all the colors to show 
through at the cuts. 
</P>
<P>
But kids, don't try this yourself. 
</P>
<P>
"The key is to have a good fabricator who has worked with the material and is 
familiar with the proper tools," Knott said. 
</P>
<P>
"You have to have a fabricator who's willing to take time and work with you and 
who knows all the wild stuff you can do with laminates. It really has to be 
handled with particular tools, so the best thing to do is to go through the 
trade." 
</P>
<P>
This generally means going to a cabinet shop, rather than a lumberyard or home 
center. 
</P>
<P>
The more generalized stores may carry some laminates, but the variety probably 
will be limited, Knott said. 
</P>
<P>
Formica isn't inexpensive. Price depends on the type and style of the material. 
But, said Knott, "it's not as (expensive) as some of the natural materials 
around. It's about neck-and-neck with wood." 
</P>
<P>
Not all Formica is doggedly contemporary, though, which ought to be good news 
for nostalgia buffs and people bent on re-creating Pop's Malt Shoppe in their 
den. In the back of the Formica color catalogue are four pages of examples with 
names like Neo Papercraft and Sorbet and Moonstone Papyrus. 
</P>
<P>
But there, at the top of the last page, is an example called Rosetta Boomerang. 
</P>
<P>
It's a deep pink shot through with intersecting yellow, blue and lavender 
parabolas. The kind of design you would have seen in Tomorrowland 35 years ago, 
a style that was known as futuristic when jet propulsion was new, the stuff 
that surely must have covered Buck Rogers' bathroom countertops. 
</P>
<P>
Formica kept it, bless them. The classics never die. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
